Word Learning - Psych Science

Kimberly A. Brink

10/25/2017

“Word Learning” is a study that assesses whether children will selectively trust a robot that provides accurate information compared to a robot that provides inaccurate information. Children watch two robots name a series of familiar objects, where one robot always names the object correctly and the other robot always incorrectly names the robot. The two robots are distingushed by their colors.

Word Learning 1: Experimental Condition

Method

Demographics

There are 67 participants.

The average age of the sample is 3.55 years.

The standard deviation age of the sample is 0.27 years.

The minimum age of the sample is 3.03 years.

The maximum age of the sample is 4 years.

There are 36 females in the sample.

Power analyses indicate that N = 33.37 is sufficient to achieve .80 statistical power with a moderate effect size of .5 and signficance level of p = .05 (Cohen, 1988).

Exclusions

1 participant was excluded for being a non-native english speaker.

6 participants asked to end early

1 participant had parent interference.

Reduced Demographics

There are now 59 participants.

The average age of the sample is 3.56 years.

The standard deviation age of the sample is 0.27 years.

The minimum age of the sample is 3.03 years.

The maximum age of the sample is 4 years.

There are 33 females in the sample.

Results

Comparisons with chance for three test questions.

Question Proportion t.df. p X95.CI
Explicit judgment 0.96 (0.03) t(52)=17.49 0 0.91,1.02

Endorse 0.68 (0.04) t(51)=4.11 0.0001 0.59,0.77

Children’s scores ranged from 0.125 to 1 (M = 0.65, SD = 0.18)

Comparisons with chance for three test questions for subset that answered first EJ question correctly.

Question Proportion t.df. p X95.CI
Ask 0.62 (0.04) t(50)=3.12 0.003 0.54,0.69
Endorse 0.69 (0.04) t(49)=4.14 0.0001 0.6,0.78

51 out of 53 children answered the first explicit judgment question correctly.

Regression Analyses

Children’s scores for Agency ranged from 0 to 3 (M = 1.82, SD = 0.91). Scores on average were different from 0, t(47) = 13.82, p = 0.

Children’s scores for Experience ranged from 0 to 3 (M = 1.99, SD = 1.02). Scores on average were different from 0, t(47) = 13.52, p = 0.
